## China's Life Expectancy Gain vs Benchmarks (1950–2023)

```         
```

`` {r} library(tidyverse)  life_exp <- read.csv("life-expectancy.csv", check.names = FALSE) names(life_exp)[4] <- "life_expectancy"  # Calculate gain from 1950 to 2023 gain_table <- life_exp |>   dplyr::filter(Year %in% c(1950, 2023)) |>   dplyr::select(Entity, Year, life_expectancy) |>   tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = Year, values_from = life_expectancy,                      names_prefix = "Year_") |>   dplyr::mutate(     `1950` = round(Year_1950, 1),     `2023` = round(Year_2023, 1),     `Gain (years)` = round(Year_2023 - Year_1950, 1),     `% Increase` = paste0(round(((Year_2023 - Year_1950) / Year_1950) * 100, 1), "%")   ) |>   dplyr::select(Entity, `1950`, `2023`, `Gain (years)`, `% Increase`)  knitr::kable(gain_table,              caption = "Life Expectancy: 1950 vs 2023 by Entity",              align = c("l", "c", "c", "c", "c"))} ``

China's life expectancy rose from **43.8 years in 1950** to **77.9 years in 2023** — a gain of over **34 years**, the largest proportional increase of any entity in the dataset. By 2023, China **surpasses the World average (73.2)** and sits **above the Upper-Middle-Income Countries benchmark (75.9)**, strongly suggesting China has converged with developed-country health outcomes.

