## Key Finding: Countries Most Similar to China in Fertility

```{r warning=FALSE, message=FALSE} library(tidyverse)  fertility <- read.csv("children-per-woman-un.csv", check.names = FALSE) names(fertility)[4] <- "fertility_rate"  china_rate <- fertility |>   dplyr::filter(Entity == "China") |>   dplyr::pull(fertility_rate)  # Summary table: 10 closest countries fertility |>   dplyr::filter(Entity != "China") |>   dplyr::mutate(diff_from_china = round(abs(fertility_rate - china_rate), 4)) |>   dplyr::arrange(diff_from_china) |>   dplyr::slice_head(n = 10) |>   dplyr::select(Country = Entity, `Fertility Rate` = fertility_rate, `Difference from China` = diff_from_china) |>   knitr::kable(caption = "Top 10 Countries with Fertility Rates Closest to China (2023)",                align = c("l", "c", "c"))}
```

China's 2023 fertility rate of **0.999** places it among the world's lowest. **Ukraine (0.977)**, **South Korea (0.720)**, **Taiwan (0.870)**, **Puerto Rico (0.941)** and **Singapore (0.943)** show the most similar fertility patterns — all experiencing severe demographic transitions driven by urbanisation, high costs of living, and shifting social norms.

